    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-03-21T08:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-03-21T08:00:00-05:00" n="502"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d502">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/1618</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_GJW1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gerard</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Berlin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-03-21T14:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 21, 1915, 2 p. m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received March 22, 5 p. m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1885. Your 1382 giving English note received.<note n="1" xml:id="d502fn1">Not
                        printed.</note> Respectfully suggest that if administration is attacked for
                    failing to go to war with England in order to force English blockade of Germany
                    you can answer that Germany has placed an embargo on so many goods which America
                    needs and has so discriminated against American goods that it hardly seems worth
                    while to go to war to keep up trade relations with a country that does not seem
                    to wish to trade with us. Note absolute embargo on potash, carbolic acid,
                    manganese hydrate, medical oil, machinery, chemicals, surgical instruments, and
                    probably five hundred other articles set forth in pamphlets already sent you or
                    on way. Only dyestuffs for a month at a time allowed out Only three hundred tons
                    cyanide a month. Absolute embargo on all intermediate dyestuffs. This put on
                    through influence <pb facs="0613" n="355" xml:id="pg_355"/> of German dyestuffs
                    trust, thinks present time apt for killing all, manufacture of dyestuffs in
                    America. For discrimination against American goods, oils, meats, provisions,
                    etc., see my reports 20 and 31, November 5 and 24, 1913, etc.<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d502fn2">Not printed.</note> Returning American ships bringing
                    cotton have to return empty because of this absolute and qualified embargo.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_GJW1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Gerard</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
